@InProceedings{SSW:Stasch,
  Title                    = {{Aggregating linked sensor data}},
  Author                   = {Stasch, Christoph and Schade, Sven and Llaves, Alejandro and Janowicz, Krzysztof and Br{\"o}ring, Arne},
  Booktitle                = {Proceedings of the 4th International Workshop on Semantic Sensor Networks},
  Year                     = {2011},
  Editor                   = {Taylor, Kerry and Ayyagari, Arun and de Roure, David},
  Pages                    = {46},

  Abstract                 = {Sensor observations are usually offered in relation to a specific purpose, e.g., for reporting fine dust emissions, following strict procedures,
and spatio-temporal scales. Consequently, the huge amount of
data gathered by today's public and private sensor networks is most often
not reused outside of its initial creation context. Fostering the reusability
of observations and derived applications calls for (i) spatial, temporal,
and thematic aggregation of measured values, and (ii) easy integration
mechanisms with external data sources. In this paper, we investigate
how work on sensor observation aggregation can be incorporated into a
Linked Data framework focusing on external linkage as well as provenance
information. We show that Linked Data adds new aspects to the
aggregation problem, e.g., whether external links from one of the original
observations can be preserved for the aggregate. The Stimulus-Sensor-
Observation (SSO) ontology design pattern is extended by classes and
relations necessary to model the aggregation of sensor observations.},
  Journal                  = {Semantic Sensor Networks},
  Owner                    = {Ivo},
  Review                   = {Fostering the reusability of observations and derived applications calls for (i) spatial, temporal, and thematic aggregation of measured values, and (ii) easy integration mechanisms with external data sources.

This paper investigates how work on sensor observation aggregation can be incorporated into a Linked Data framework focusing on external linkage as well as provenance information. 

In other communities, e.g., the database community or in environmental sciences, spatio-temporal aggregation has been a research topic for years and is sometimes also referred to as scaling of observations and environmental models. A spatio-temporal aggregation service that can be used to provide such aggregation functionality on the Sensor Web has been introduced in our previous work (towards a spatiotemporal aggregation service in the sensor web, 2011).

Definition of aggregation: During an aggregation process, the observations are grouped by a grouping predicate, e.g., by a spatial predicate which is defned by the polygon representing the area of a city, or by a temporal predicate defned by the time period of a month. After grouping, an aggregation function is applied that computes a single value, an aggregate, for the result values of an observation group. 

For aggregation of observations a mechanism that helps to retrace the original observations and sensors from the aggregated observations is important. Linked Data provides a promising paradigm to provide such a mechanism, as the original observations and the aggregates can be easily linked with clear semantics.

Provenance of sensor data can be defned as information about the source of the sensor data as well as information about transformations applied to the original data. The proposed approach shows how most of relevant provenance information is already provided in our Linked Sensor Data and how the links can be mapped to provenance relationships as defned in the OPM (Open Provenance Model).

The main contributions of this paper are threefold. They (i) present a Linked Data model for aggregated sensor data, (ii) discuss the effects of aggregation on links from and to observations, and (iii) outline the role of provenance in this setting.

The authors have extende the W3C SSO (SSN) ontology with 4 extra classes: isAggregateOf, SensingDevice, ggregationProcess and AggregationProcedure.},
  Timestamp                = {2015.11.27}
}

